<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41784239</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>06</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>06</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">2724-7031</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>103</Volume><Issue>6</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Jun</Month><Day>05</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>La Tunisie medicale</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Tunis Med</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>[Not Available].</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>789</StartPage><EndPage>795</EndPage><MedlinePgn>789-795</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.62438/tunismed.v103i6.5682</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="INTRODUCTION" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">Pneumothorax (PNO) is a common pathology in clinical practice. The therapeutic approach to PNO depends on the patient's clinical conditions, the extent of the disease, and the presence or absence of underlying pulmonary comorbidity.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="AIM" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">To report the epidemiological and therapeutic profile of patients treated for spontaneous pneumothorax in a university hospital in a city in southern Tunisia.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHOD" NlmCategory="METHODS">This is a retrospective descriptive study involving patients hospitalized for spontaneous PNO in the pulmonology department between January 2020 and December 2021.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">During the study period, there were 56 admissions for spontaneous PNO. Men were more affected than women (94.6%). The average age of the patients was 43 years old. Seventy-four percent of patients lived within a 10 km radius of the Gabes industrial zone. Smoking was noted in 85.71% of patients. Nineteen patients (33.9%) had respiratory comorbidities such as PNO (21.4%), chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) (7.1%) and covid19 pneumonia (7.1%). PNO was classified as primary in 41 patients (73.21%) and secondary in 15 patients (26.78%). The clinical symptoms were dominated by chest pain in 98.2% of cases, dyspnea 82.1% and cough 41.1%. The clinical tolerance of PNO was good in 80.4% of cases. The course of action was bed rest with high-flow oxygen therapy in 12 patients (21.4%) with partial and well-tolerated PNO. Chest drainage was performed as first intention in 44 patients (78.6%). The average time to return to the wall was 4 days. A pleurodesis procedure was indicated in 17 patients (30.4%). In the patients followed (85.7%), a recurrence of PNO was observed in 5 patients (10.4%).</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Majdoub Fehri</LastName><ForeName>Sabrine</ForeName><Initials>S</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Pneumology, University Hospital of Gab&#xe8;s, Faculty of Medicine of Sfax, Faculty of Sfax, Tunisia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Issaoui</LastName><ForeName>Nawress</ForeName><Initials>N</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Pneumology, University Hospital of Gab&#xe8;s, Faculty of Medicine of Sfax, Faculty of Sfax, Tunisia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kwas</LastName><ForeName>Hamida</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Pneumology, University Hospital of Gab&#xe8;s, Faculty of Medicine of Sfax, Faculty of Sfax, Tunisia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>fre</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D004740">English Abstract</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><VernacularTitle>Clinical, therapeutic and evolutionary profile of spontaneous pneumothorax.</VernacularTitle><ArticleDate DateT